AGI - The candidate Jeremiah Manele was elected Prime Minister of Solomon Islands. In the secret ballot in Parliament, the former diplomat won 31 out of 50 votes, surpassing his rival Mathew Wale, who had promised a loosening of ties with Beijing. "People have spoken," said Manele, delighted that the vote has taken place without violence: "Today we have shown the world that we are better than this." In the Solomon Islands, the island nation of Oceania of about 720 thousand inhabitants, the elections are often accompanied by tumults.
&nbsp;
In 2000, Prime Minister Bart Ulufa'alu was forced to resign after being kidnapped by armed men and in 2006 an international contingent was deployed to avoid revolts. Manele was Minister of Foreign Affairs in 2019, when the Solomon Islands moved away from Taiwan by establishing diplomatic relations with Beijing. Analysts expect Manele to continue the approach policy to China initiated by his predecessor Manasseh Sogavare, who did not return, with the agreement on security signed with the Dragon in 2022.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The details of this agreement remain obscure but the US and Australia fear that the pact has placed the first stone for the construction of a permanent Chinese military base in the southern Pacific. The elected prime minister promised a "national unity government" that will focus on relaunching the economy and on the "progress on the road of recovery" from the Covid-19 pandemic. A reform of value-added tax and the creation of a special economic zone are among the priorities announced by the new government.
